Overview

Letâs get some practice going through a complete data analysis project from start to finish. We will explore, visualize, clean, and train models for a regression application. Specifically, we will predictive the compressive strength of concrete using a widely available and popular data set. This report demonstrates preparing data for predictive models, and considers various kinds of preprocessing steps that we should consider. Linear methods and advanced non-linear methods are used, many of which you will learn more about later in the course.

We will work with the tidymodels library in this report. tidymodels is a suite of packages that provide modeling workflows following the tidyverse philosophy and mindset. Numerous packages will be used within this report, most but not all are installed with tidymodels. The code chunk below loads in tidymodels and so brings in a suite of packages that will we will work with. Additional packages will be loaded later in the report.

As shown above, the age variable has just 14 unique values, while all other variables have at least one hundred values or more. We might be tempted to view the age variable has categorical because there are relatively few unique values. However, it is also important to know and understand the context of a data set and the application we are working on. The age variable is fundamentally numeric, providing the time (referred to as the âageâ) of a concrete specimen when it is tested. The fact that there are just 14 values for age represents the common times used in the industry that produces concrete.

This is a supervised learning or predictive modeling application. Thus, some variables are inputs, while another variable is an output, response, or outcome of interest. In this specific application, we want to predict or model the compressive_strength as a function of the other variables in the data set.

The previous table showed the number of unique values for each variable. Letâs now consider the number of unique combinations of all inputs. As shown below, there are 992 unique combinations of the 8 inputs. The concrete data has 1030 rows, thus some combinations are replicated multiple times.

concrete %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  dim()
## [1] 992   8

From a statistical point of view, replication is a good thing. Replication allows us to consider the repeability (or lack there of) of an experiment, configuration, design, or process. The code chunk below identifies the unique input configurations, and displays to the screen the number of configurations that have been replicated more than once.

concrete_configs <- concrete %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  group_by(across()) %>% 
  summarise(num_rows = n(), .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column("set_id")

concrete_configs %>%

It is important to note that the 4 rows shown above are not duplicates. They are replications. Although the response, compressive_strength is also constant for the specific input configuration, we must also check the response behavior of the other 18 replicated configurations. The code chunk below visualizes the compressive_strength as a strip plot for the 19 replicated input configurations. As reference, the count (number of observations) is represented by the marker size. The minimum and maximum response values per configuration are connected by a vertical grey line to better visualize the range. The minimum and maximum values associated with compressive_strength are displayed by horizontal grey lines to give further context about the magnitude of the variation. As shown below, there are multiple configurations with identical values for the response, and thus no variation across the replications. However, there are also configurations with different response values even though the input configurations are the same! Several configurations appear to have small variation (about 5 units or less), while others have moderate variation (about 10 units). One configuration, set_id = 784, has a range (difference between max and min) of more than 20 units! If we were working with this dataset at a company or in a research project, we would want to learn more about the data collection and entry process to make sure an error did not occur when the low value with set_id = 784 was recorded.

concrete %>% 
  left_join(concrete_configs,
            by = input_names) %>% 
  filter(num_rows > 1) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(set_id), y = compressive_strength)) +
  stat_summary(geom = 'linerange',
               fun.min = min, fun.max = max,
               mapping = aes(group = set_id),
               color = 'grey', size = 1.1) +
  geom_count() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = range(concrete$compressive_strength),
             color = 'grey', linetype = 'dashed', size = 1.2) +
  theme_bw()

The above figure reveals a grouping of the replication variability: no variation, small, moderate, and the extreme variation. It would be interesting to check if such grouping structure was associated with an interval of one of the inputs or combination of a few inputs. However, we will not go examine such behavior in this report.

We must decide how we will handle the replicate variations in our data set. The correct approach would be to include the replication variability as an unknown parameter, separate from the residual error of the model. We would therefore handle the hierarchical structure of the data: variation due to changing the inputs, and the natural process variation which is natural in all manufacturing processes (if you are interested the field of statistical quality or process control is focused on monitoring and understand drivers of variability). However, appropriately capturing the two sources of error is outside the scope of this example. Instead, we will follow the same simplification used in Ch. 15 in the tidy modeling with R book, namely we will average the response of the replicate configurations. The tidy modeling with R book (tmwr) describes averaging the response so that the cross-validation strategy will not yield overconfident performance metrics due to configurations with no variability having the same response value. This is a valid concern, but if we approapriately handled the hierarchical nature of the data, the cross-validation would be applied to unique configurations, not necessarily individual measurements. Again, we will not go into such an approach here, and so we will simply average the response as done in tmwr.

Before averaging, letâs visualize the average response and the confidence interval on the average for the replicate configurations. This will help us understand the consequence of our choice, relative to the original raw measurements. The average and confidence interval are dispalyed by the red marker and error bars in the graph below. As we can see, the mean is a good proxy for the configurations with small response variability. However, the moderate variability configurations show the mean may not be representative of any of the measurements. This is especially true for set_id = 784 where the mean is obviously different from the extreme lower measurement value.

concrete %>% 
  left_join(concrete_configs,
            by = input_names) %>% 
  filter(num_rows > 1) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = as.factor(set_id), y = compressive_strength)) +
  stat_summary(geom = 'linerange',
               fun.min = min, fun.max = max,
               mapping = aes(group = set_id),
               color = 'grey', size = 1.1) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_summary(fun.data = 'mean_se',
               color = 'red',
               mapping = aes(group = set_id),
               fun.args = list(mult = 2)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = range(concrete$compressive_strength),
             color = 'grey', linetype = 'dashed', size = 1.2) +
  theme_bw()

We are âsplitting the differenceâ between measurements by âreplacingâ the raw measurements with the grouped average response per input configuration. Having to make such choices are common in data analysis applications. By using the average and ignoring the replication variability we will be under representing the uncertainty in the response. This is acceptable for now because we are primarily demonstrating the approach. A complete analysis would require that we also consider the hierarchical nature of the data.

The code chunk below performs the averaging and assigns the result to the my_concrete object.

my_concrete <- concrete %>% 
  group_by(across(cement:age)) %>% 
  summarise(compressive_strength = mean(compressive_strength),
            .groups = 'drop')

Letâs confirm the number of rows in the prepared data set is less than what we had originally.

my_concrete %>% dim()
## [1] 992   9
nrow(my_concrete) < nrow(concrete)
## [1] TRUE

These three variables have complicated distributions. They are mixtures. First thereâs a categorical representation, âdoes the value equal zero?â. If the value is greater than zero, the three have continuous distributions. Working with such mixture type inputs can be challenging.

The number of identically zero observations presented above do not consider combinations of the variables. We focused on each variable separately. Letâs now consider if the three variables frequently equal zero at the same time. The graphic below visualizes the counts of equal to zero or not equal to zero with a bar chart. The counts associated with blast_furnace_slag are represented by the facets. This suggests there is a relationship for how the binarized version of the variables are structured.

We can focus just on the correlation coefficients with a correlation plot. The corrplot package provides streamlined functions dedicated to visualization correlation plots. Please download and install corrplot to run the code chunk below. Correlation plots are important because we must always consider if inputs are highly correlated or not before we train models. Correlated inputs can make interpretation difficult, impact the uncertainty in parameter estimates, and at worst cause numerical issues with the model fitting procedure. As a general rule of thumb, if inputs/features have correlation coefficients greater than 0.8 or so, we should consider approaches that are dedicated to handling highly correlated variables. As shown by the correlation plot below, it seems that we do not need to worry about such issues currently.

my_concrete %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  cor() %>% 
  corrplot::corrplot(method = 'number', type = 'upper', tl.cex = 0.55)

The corrplot package is useful because it is so streamlined. However, sometimes we need greater control when creating correlation plots. For example, corrplot is difficult to use when we want to create grouped correlation plots. The code chunk below uses corrr (part of tidymodels) and tidyr (part of the tidyverse) to examine if the input correlation coefficients change based on if blast_furnace_slag equals zero or not. The displayed warning message tells us that a variable has zero standard deviation when blast_furnace_slag == 0. A warning message appears because when blast_furnace_slag == 0, that variable by definition has zero variation. That is why grey boxes appear in the blast_furnace_slag == 0 facet.

my_concrete %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  group_by(blast_furnace_slag == 0) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = map(data, corrr::correlate, quiet = TRUE, diagonal = 1),
         cor_lf = map(cor_wf, corrr::stretch)) %>% 
  select(`blast_furnace_slag == 0`, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r),
            color = 'white') +
  facet_wrap( ~ `blast_furnace_slag == 0`, labeller = "label_both") +
  scale_fill_gradient2('corr',
                       low = 'red', mid = 'white', high = 'blue',
                       midpoint = 0,
                       limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(x='', y='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5, size=4.5),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 5.5))
## Warning in stats::cor(x = x, y = y, use = use, method = method): the standard
## deviation is zero

Sometimes it can be useful to focus on the absolute value of the correlation coefficient. This streamlines the visualization. Furthermore, a discretized color scale can help us understand if the value is above thresholds of interest. The graphic below shows the same grouped correlation plot, but the tile fill corresponds to the correlation coefficient absolute value and the discrete color scale highlights if the correlation coefficient is above 0.8 or not. As shown below, it does not appear that we have very high correlation coefficients even when considering the grouping of blast_furnace_slag == 0. We could continue visualizing such groupings, but we will conclude this exploration for now.

my_concrete %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  group_by(blast_furnace_slag == 0) %>% 
  tidyr::nest() %>% 
  mutate(cor_wf = map(data, corrr::correlate, quiet = TRUE, diagonal = 1),
         cor_lf = map(cor_wf, corrr::stretch)) %>% 
  select(`blast_furnace_slag == 0`, cor_lf) %>% 
  tidyr::unnest(cor_lf) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(r_bin = cut(abs(r),
                     breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.2),
                     include.lowest = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_tile(mapping = aes(fill = r_bin),
            color = 'white') +
  facet_wrap( ~ `blast_furnace_slag == 0`, labeller = "label_both") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("abs(corr)") +
  labs(x='', y='') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=0.5, size=4.5),

Exploration conclusion

It would be best to continue visually exploring the relationships. However, we will conclude this exercise for now. Our major findings is that several of the variables have challenging âmixtureâ type distributions and age has relatively few unique values. The mixture type distributions will complicate the analysis. The response, compressive_strength, appears to have a non-linear relationship with age. The strength appears to have a linear trend with cement. The slope of that relationship does not appear to be strongly influenced by age, but we will need to models to confirm if that is the case or not. Importantly, we have identified that the 8 inputs are not highly correlated with each other.

Predictive modeling

We will train multiple models, ranging from simple to complex. This will allow us to understand the kinds of features required to appropriately model the trends and relationships between the inputs and response. We do not want to simply overfit to the training data, and so we will assess model performance via a resampling scheme. The resampling procedure will also allow us to tune hyperparameters which cannot be easily estimated when the models are fit.

The tmwr book in Chapter 15 used an initial train/test split, followed by 5-fold cross-validation. I prefer to work with repeated cross-validation instead of the initial train/test split approach. We will discuss the merits of such approaches throughout the course. The code chunk below defines an object which captures how the complete data set, my_concrete, will be resampled multiple times. Specifically, we will use 5-fold with 5-repeats. The response, compressive_strength, is used as a stratification variable to help make sure the splits roughly capture the same spread in the response. The cv_folds object includes columns, id and id2, that identify the splits. The id2 columns gives the fold-id within a repeat identfied by the id column.

set.seed(2021)
cv_folds <- vfold_cv(my_concrete, v = 5, repeats = 5, strata = compressive_strength)

Before training, it is best to decide how we will assess the model performance. We must consider performance metrics appropriate for a regression problem. We will compare model performance via root mean square error (RMSE), R-squared, and the mean absolute error (MAE). The RMSE and MAE focus on individual point-wise accuracy. The MAE is less influenced by extreme values (outliers). The lower the RMSE or MAE the better. The R-squared (also known as the coefficient of determination) does not consider point-wise accuracy. Instead, R-squared measures the correlation between the model prediction and the observations. R-squared is simply the square of the correlation coefficient between the model prediction and the observed value. It is between 0 and 1; the closer the value to 1 the better the model is performing. It is important to consider multiple performance metrics when comparing models. Each metric provides a slightly different interpretation of the behavior. Using multiple performance metrics allows us consider potential trade-offs when we ultimately select a model or models to focus on.

The code chunk below defines the metric set we will use to assess performance.

my_metrics <- metric_set(rmse, rsq, mae)

Linear methods

Although it is common to think of preprocessing as a separate action from models, we should view preprocessing as an integral aspect of the type of models we train. Afterall, using a different set of preprocessing actions may yield different behavior and thus performance from the same type of model. In this section, we will train linear models but with different types of predictors or features derived from the inputs. The features will be created within a recipe object to allow preprocessing actions such as centering and scaling to be performed within each resample fold during training.

Linear additive relationships

We will start with a simple model with linear additive features. This model cannot handle non-linear trends between the response and inputs, and cannot capture any type of interaction between inputs. Our exploratory data analysis (EDA) revealed non-linearities are present between the response and age. Thus, we should expect the linear additive model to perform poorly in this application. However, I always recommend starting with this model because it is easy to fit and train, simple to interpret, and serves as a useful benchmark case. We can judge the performance of more advanced models based on the improvement relative to this simple model.

In the tidymodels framework, we will first define the linear model engine and specification we wish to use.

lm_spec <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm")

Next, letâs create a recipe object which standardizes the inputs and produces the additive features.

bp_stan <- recipe(compressive_strength ~ ., data = my_concrete) %>% 
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_scale(all_predictors())

We can always check we are getting the features we want by âpreppingâ the recipe and âbakingâ it into the data. The code chunk below preps, bakes, and displays the names of the columns of the standardized training set.

check_stan_df <- bp_stan %>% 
  prep(training = my_concrete, retain = TRUE) %>% 
  bake(new_data = NULL)

check_stan_df %>% names()

Before training the model we will define a workflow which understands that our complete model consists of a set of preprocessing steps and a specific model type.

lm_add_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_stan)

The workflow is an object that understands the steps or algorithm required. Printing lm_add_wflow to the screen describes all of the actions that the model will perform.

We will now fit the model and assess the performance using the repeated cross-validation strategy. The code chunk below uses the fit_resamples() function to fit (train) and assess the performance. It is important to note that the my_concrete object is provided to fit_resamples() not the check_stan_df object. The check_stan_df data set has the standardization already applied (or âbakedâ in to follow the tidymodels love of puns). We want the preprocessing steps to be applied within each resample fold. The workflow, lm_add_wflow, knows the preprocessing actions to take and will apply the standardization based on each foldâs specific training set. Thus, our complete model of preprocessing and model type will correctly account for the potential differences between the training and test set! We will discuss why it is important to apply the preprocessing within each fold near the end of the semester when we discuss PCA in greater detail.

lm_add_res <- lm_add_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(cv_folds,
                metrics = my_metrics)

The lm_add_res object stores the results associated with each resample split.

bp_pairs <- bp_stan %>%

All triplet interactions

The previous modelâs features included muliplications between two inputs. We could also consider the product of three inputs! This type of model represents that the trend between the response and an input depends on two other inputs.

The code chunk below creates the recipe for the triplet interaction starting from the standardized inputs. The triplet interaction product will include all main-effect and pair-wise interaction terms.

bp_trips <- bp_stan %>% 
  step_interact( ~ all_predictors():all_predictors():all_predictors())

Letâs bake-in this recipe to see just how many features are present in a model which includes up to all triplet interactions. The code chunk below prints the number of features (after the response is removed) to the screen. Even though our application has 8 inputs, allowing all triplet interactions creates a model with 92 features!

bp_trips %>% 
  prep(training = my_concrete, retain = TRUE) %>% 
  bake(new_data = NULL) %>% 
  select(-compressive_strength) %>% 
  ncol()
## [1] 92

The triplet interaction model workflow is created below.

lm_trips_wflow <- workflow() %>%

lm_trips_res <- lm_trips_wflow %>%

Response surface methods

Response surface methods (RSM) are classic statistical models historically used to optimize manufacturing and process control systems. Although RSMs have their own name and terminology, they are simply linear models with interactions and polynomial features. Thus, we can fit response surfaces using the exact same techniques we used previously. We just need to include polynomial features in the recipe. We will use response surfaces as our first attempt to capture non-linear relationships between the response and the inputs. We saw in the EDA that the response appears non-linearly related to age and so we will use polynomial features to try and represent that relationship.

The code chunk below creates the recipe for a quadratic response surface and a cubic response surface. The quadratic model includes all pair-wise interactions, and the cubic model includes all triplet interactions.

bp_rsm_2 <- bp_stan %>% 
  step_poly(all_predictors(), degree = 2,
            options = list(raw = TRUE)) %>% 
  step_interact(~ends_with("_poly_1"):ends_with("_poly_1"))

bp_rsm_3 <- bp_stan %>% 
  step_poly(all_predictors(), degree = 3,
            options = list(raw = TRUE)) %>% 
  step_interact(~ends_with("_poly_1"):ends_with("_poly_1"):ends_with("_poly_1"))

The RSM workflows are created below.

rsm_2_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_rsm_2)

rsm_3_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_rsm_3)

The RSMs are trained and assessed in the code chunk below.

rsm_2_res <- rsm_2_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(cv_folds,
                metrics = my_metrics)

rsm_3_res <- rsm_3_wflow %>% 
  fit_resamples(cv_folds,
                metrics = my_metrics)

All three performance metrics yield consistent behavior. The cubic RSM has the best performance, followed by the quadratic RSM, then the interaction models, and lastly the linear additive features model. Note that the quadratic RSM out-performs the triplet interaction model. This represents that the non-linear features are more important than the triplet interactions since the quadratic RSM does not include triplet interactions. The cubic RSM is the most complex model, since all other models we have tried are subsets of the cubic RSM. However, that additional complexity is worth it! The most complex model tried so far not only out performs the others, but we are rather confident in it being better than the others!

Penalized regression - Elastic net

The cubic RSM is the most complex model we have tried so far, because it has more features than any other model. It also âcontainsâ all other models. Even though we have seen the cubic RSM is the best performing model so far, are all features truly necessary? What are the minimum set of features required to maintain the performance of the cubic RSM? Or, put another way which features can be âturned offâ?

Penalized or regularized regression models attempt to answer these questions. We will discuss how the penalty works and how to interpret it later in the semester. For now we will focus on training the model and tuning the hyperparameters that define how the model is fit. We will use the elastic net model from the glmnet package, and so you must have downloaded and installed glmnet to run the following examples.
Elastic net consists of two tuning parameters. The first is the penalty factor (referred to as lambda by the glmnet authors), which controls the strength of the penalty term. Stronger penalties will turn off more features and can ultimately remove all trends in the model if allowed. The second is the mixture fraction (referred to as alpha by the glmnet authors) which is a weighting term between two types of penalties. One penalty (known as ridge) is useful for computational reasons, while the other (known as lasso) is the model selection penalty which forces unimportant features to zero.

tidymodels includes default bounds on the tuning parameters. For example the bounds on the penalty factor are:

penalty()
## Amount of Regularization (quantitative)
## Transformer:  log-10 
## Range (transformed scale): [-10, 0]

The default bounds on the mixing fraction are shown below.

mixture()
## Proportion of lasso Penalty (quantitative)
## Range: [0, 1]

We do not know the best values of the tuning parameters up front. We will use a simple approach to tune the model by defining a search grid. We will create combinations of the two tuning parameters, train and assess the model for each combination using resampling. We will then select the tuning parameter values that give the best performance averaged over the resamples. In this way, we are essentially treating each tuning parameter combination set as a separate model.

We can create a search grid using the default bounds, but instead letâs modify the bounds as shown below.

my_lambda <- penalty(range = c(-10.5, 2), trans = log_trans())

my_alpha <- mixture(range = c(0.1, 1.0))

We will use a search grid consisting of 75 unique penalty values and 5 values for the mixing fraction. The glimpse printed to the screen below shows that we are therefore trying \(75\times5=375\) combinations of the two parameters. We are essentially training and assessing 375 separate models even though all models are the same type (elastic net) and have the same set of features.

enet_grid <- grid_regular(my_lambda, my_alpha, 
                          levels = c(penalty = 75, mixture = 5))

enet_grid %>% glimpse()

Before we train and assess the elastic net model, letâs get some intuition for what itâs doing. The code chunk below fits a pure lasso model to the entire data set and examines how the penalty term impacts the coefficients. The penalty (referred to as lambda by glmnet) increases left to right in the figure below. Each curve corresponds to the coefficient value associated with a feature. The left hand side has the smallest penalty value and the right hand side has the largest penalty. The numbers on the upper x-axis correspond to the number of non-zero coefficients. As the penalty increases more and more features are âturned offâ, as represented by the number of non-zero coefficients decreasing left-to-right. Large penalty values are capable of turning off all but the most essential features!

lasso_fit <- enet_wflow %>% 
  update_model(linear_reg(penalty = 0.1, mixture = 1) %>% 
                 set_engine("glmnet",
                            intercept = TRUE, standardize.response = TRUE, standardize = TRUE,
                            path_values = exp(seq(-10.5, 2, length.out = 75)))) %>% 
  fit(my_concrete)

lasso_fit %>% extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  pluck("fit") %>% 
  plot(xvar = 'lambda')

The figure above is referred to as the coefficient path. It shows how the model âevolvesâ and changes under different penalty assumptions. As stated earlier, we do not know what penalty value is best ahead of time. We know that small penalties allow more features, while large penalties focus just on the most essential features. Resampling will help us pick the value to use by focusing on the performance rather than the coefficient values as the penalty changes.

We are going to try out 375 separate tuning parameter combinations with 5-fold cross-validation repeated 5 times. That means we are fittina and evaluating the model \(375\times5\times5=9375\) times! This might take a while, so we can run everything in parallel to speed it up. The code chunk below creates the parallel backend if there are more than 3 physical cores present in the machine. I created this RMarkdown on a Windows desktop, but the code chunk below should work on other operating systems. If you have a Mac there are other dedicated parallel backends that you can use if you prefer. The tmwr book shows how to setup the parallel backend on multiple operating systems. I chose to use two minus the make number of physical cores on the machine. You may change that if you wish. If the machine has 2 or fewer physical cores, no parallel computation will be setup.

if(parallel::detectCores(logical=FALSE) > 3){
  library(doParallel)
  
  num_cores <- parallel::detectCores(logical=FALSE)
  cl <- makePSOCKcluster(num_cores - 2)
  registerDoParallel(cl)
}

However, we could also identify the tuning parameters that are âwithin the margin of errorâ of the absolute best performance. This concept is known as the â1-standard error ruleâ. The idea is we prefer simpler models, over more complicated models as one final safe-guard against overfitting. In the context of regularized regression, larger penalty values force more terms to zero and thus create simpler models! Thus, we would like a simpler model that has an average performance metric within 1-standard error of the best average performance metric value.

enet_res %>% select_by_one_std_err(desc(penalty), desc(mixture), metric = 'rmse')
## # A tibble: 1 x 10

##     <dbl>   <dbl> <chr>   <chr>      <dbl> <int>   <dbl> <chr>      <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1  0.0465       1 rmse    standard    6.57    25   0.105 Preproces~  6.49   6.60

Non-linear methods

Now that we have tried out multiple linear methods, it is time to see if we more advanced non-linear approaches can give us even better results. The methods we will use next are those typically considered when we say âmachine learningâ. However, it is important to note our linear methods were capable of achieving an R-squared of about 83% on average on new data (as estimated by repeated cross-validation). The linear model commonly thought of with linear additive features was capable of an R-squared of about 60%. We know interactions and non-linearity are important, but we will now see if advanced methods can outperform the parametric expressions.

Neural network

We will use a single hidden layer feed forward neural network. tidymodels denotes this as the multilayer perceptron (mlp). There are several computational engines available for neural networks, at the moment within tidymodels. The keras engine is the keras API built on top of TensorFlow, and thus we can train TensorFlow neural networks with tidymodels if we would like. This report however will use the nnet engine which uses the nnet package. Please download and install the nnet package if you would like to run this example yourself.

show_engines('mlp')
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##   engine mode          
##   <chr>  <chr>         
## 1 keras  classification
## 2 keras  regression    
## 3 nnet   classification
## 4 nnet   regression

We will learn about the computational details of neural networks later in the semester. For now, we will focus on that we must specify the number of hidden units (neurons), the regularization (penalty factor), and the number of epochs (the number of iterations to use). All three options can be tuned, but we will simplify the approach for now by fixing the epochs to 2000. In truth, the nnet package treats this as the maximum number of iterations and so fewer iterations may be used. We will discuss issues around the number of iterations and epochs later in the semester. The neural network model is specified in the code chunk below.

nnet_spec <- mlp(hidden_units = tune(), penalty = tune(), epochs = 2000) %>% 
  set_engine("nnet", MaxNWts = 2500, trace=FALSE) %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

We will again use a simple grid search to tune the model. The grid will consist of combinations of the number of hidden units and the penalty factor. The default bounds on the number of hidden units are:

hidden_units()
## # Hidden Units (quantitative)
## Range: [1, 10]

Those are useful bounds to start with to help minimize the run time, but letâs allow for more complicated and flexible behavior by allowing up to 30 hidden units. The penalty factor will help regularize the added flexibility. The code chunk below creates the search grid using the crossing() from function the tidyr package (which is part of the tidyverse). As shown by the glimpse below, we will try 105 tuning parameter combinations.

nnet_grid <- crossing(hidden_units = c(5, 10, 15, 25, 30),
                      penalty = 10^(seq(-10, 1.75, length.out = 21)))

The neural network workflow is created in the code chunk below. We do not use the RSM recipes. Instead, we simply use the standardized recipe, bp_stan. As we will learn later in the semester, the neural network consists of linear combinations of non-linear transformation of linear combinations of the inputs. We therefore do not need to create interactions or polynomial terms.

nnet_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(nnet_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_stan)

The neural network is trained and assessed in the code chunk below. The random seed is set to help control the initialization of the neural network weights and biases. Please be advised this may take awhile to complete, especially if you cannot run in parallel.

Letâs now examine the neural network performance for the different number of hidden units and penalty values.

nnet_res %>% collect_metrics() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = log10(penalty))) +
  geom_ribbon(mapping = aes(group = interaction(hidden_units, .metric),
                            fill = as.factor(hidden_units),

                            ymax = mean + std_err),
              alpha = 0.4) +

                          y = mean),

  scale_color_viridis_d("Hidden units") +
  labs(y = 'performance metric value') +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

The neural network with 10 hidden units certainly acts strangely in terms of RMSE. Notice that the MAE behavior appears more âstableâ, which is consistent with the MAE being less sensitive to extreme values. The penalty term serves a similar role to that described with elastic net, since it is trying to restrict complexity. We will focus on how the penalty term accomplishes that later in the semester. What you should focus on at the moment is how the performance metric changes as the penalty changes. For example, with 30 hidden units the performance is âbouncing aroundâ until a log10(penalty) value of -5. Then the performance improves as the penalty increases, before achieving peak performance near the penalty value of 1 (log10(0)=1). Increasing the penalty further causes the performance to get worse, as shown by the MAE increasing rapidly for log10(penalty)>0. The penalty controls complexity, low values represent greater complexity and large values represent simplicity. The above figure illustrates that overly complex models can overfit, while overly simple models can underfit. We wish to strike a balance and find the most flexible yet simple model that generalizes to new data. This concept, also referred to as the bias-variance trade-off, exists for all types of models. For this application, the neural network tuning behavior perfectly illustrated the concept. We will discuss this idea many times throughout the semester.

Letâs go ahead and identify the tuning parameters that minimize the resampling averaged RMSE. We could make use of the one standard error rule again, but we will select the best overall performance for simplicity with the neural network. The neural network workflow is âfinalizedâ with those selected tuning parameters.

  finalize_workflow(nnet_lowest_rmse_params)

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

The SVM can be viewed as an entire modeling framework, rather than a single type of model. In laymanâs terms, the beauty of the SVM lies with the fact that the user is free to select a kernel to represent similarity. The kernel can be linear, highly non-linear, focus on smooth behavior, or handle jumps and discontinuous behavior. The user is free to choose and compare different kernels to identify the best model. Two popular kernels are the polynomial kernel and the radial basis function (RBF) (also referred to as a Gaussian kernel). We will focus here just on the RBF.

The SVM RBF has three tuning parameters, the âsigmaâ, the âcostâ, and the âmarginâ (usually referred to as epsilon in the SVM literature). To get a sense for the scale of the âsigmaâ parameter letâs go ahead and fit a SVM RBF using the entire training set and representative values for the cost and margin parameters. It is important to use standardized inputs with SVM RBF, and so the bp_stan recipe object is used within the workflow definition. We are using the kernlab package as the engine, so please download and install kernlab to run the code chunk below.

rbf_default <- svm_rbf(cost = 1, margin = 1) %>% 
  set_engine('kernlab') %>% 
  set_mode('regression')

rbf_default_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rbf_default) %>% 
  add_recipe(bp_stan)

rbf_default_fit <- rbf_default_wflow %>% fit(my_concrete)

Random forest

Random forests are extensions of recursive partitioning trees and bootstrap aggregation (bagging). Random forests are ensembles that try to overcome overfitting by averaging together many overfit models. This approach sounds counter intuitive, but we will see later in the semester how such an approach is enabled by the bootstrap. We will discuss the tuning parameters associated with random forest later in the semester. For now, focus on that as a tree based method random forest does not require preprocessing like the other models we have used. It does not have many tuning parameters. The most important one, mtry, is easier to interpret and we will spend some time later in the semester discussing itâs significance.

Letâs go ahead and define the model and the workflow. We will use the ranger package and so please download and install ranger before running these examples.

rf_spec <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), min_n = tune(), trees = 1000) %>% 
  set_engine("ranger") %>% 
  set_mode('regression')

rf_wflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_spec) %>% 
  add_formula(compressive_strength ~ .)

The mtry tuning parameter is best to define after the workflow has been defined. Again, we will discuss why that is later in the semester.

rf_param <- rf_spec %>% parameters() %>% finalize(my_concrete)

Gradient boosted trees

Boosted trees are another class of ensemble method. Rather than averaging over many overfit models, the boosted tree sequentially combines many underfit models together. Each tree improves slightly improves the error of the previous tree in a long chain. A popular implementation of the gradient boosted tree is XGBoost. We will discuss XGBoost in depth later in the semester, but you should be aware that it has many tuning parameters. XGBoost can be quite powerful, but it takes more care and effort to properly tune compared to the random forest. We will not tune all possible parameters in this example. We will focus on the most important ones: the number of iterations (number of trees), the tree depth (which represents complexity), the learning rate (how quickly the error reduces), mtry, and sample_size. The XGBoost model is created with the xgboost package, so please download and install xgboost before running the example below.

The boosted tree model is specified in the code chunk below.

xgb_spec <- boost_tree(tree_depth = tune(), learn_rate = tune(), 
                       trees = tune(), mtry = tune(), sample_size = tune()) %>% 
  set_engine("xgboost") %>% 
  set_mode("regression")

The tuning parameter grid is defined below.

Variable importances

Now that we know which models are best, letâs examine which inputs are most important. We will focus on the top three models, XGBoost, random forest, and the neural network. The variable importances are extracted with the vip package, which should be downloaded and installed with tidymodels. Please double check before running the code chunks below.

library(vip)

The three variable importance plots are arranged side-by-side in the graphic below. The exact values of th importances are not necessarily what we want to focus on right now. Instead, we are primarily interested in the ordering. Regardless of the model, the variable with the highest absolute importance value is considered the most important input. All three models agree that age is the most important input. Also, all three models agree that cement is the second most important input. The tree-based methods agree that water is the third most important input, but the neural network considers blast_furnace_slag to be the third most important input. Please note that the variable importance method used for the neural network model considers the magnitude and sign of the importance. That is why the water variable is listed at the bottom of the NNET plot.

  theme_bw()

grid.arrange(nnet_vip, rf_vip, xgb_vip, ncol = 3)

I like to examine the variable importances associated with several top performing models. I am mainly looking for consistency in the rankings. For this application, it is nice to see that the top two inputs are agreed upon by the best models.

Predictive trends

Letâs make predictions with our top three models to help provide additional context to the variable importance rankings. Afterall, we know that the XGBoost model is considered the best. The XGBoost variable importance rankings are slightly different from the random forest model, but the overall rankings are still similar. The neural network and random forest rankings however are different, except for the top two as described above. Letâs see if predictions can help us understand why.

We will examine the predictive trends associated with the top three ranked inputs according to the XGBoost model. The rest of the inputs will be set equal to their training set median values. The prediction grid is created in the code chunk below.
